'''Danilo dos Santos de Oliveira''' (born 29 April 2001), known simply as '''Danilo''', '''Danilo Oliveira''' or '''Danilo Santos''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fogaonet.com/noticias-do-botafogo/danilo-botafogo-vira-danilo-santos-selecao-brasileira-comeca-banco-amistoso-franca/ |title=Danilo, do Botafogo, vira 'Danilo Santos' na Seleção Brasileira e começa no banco em amistoso com a França  |trans-title=Danilo, from Botafogo, becomes ‘Danilo Santos’ in the Brazilian National Team and starts on the bench in a friendly against France. |website=FogãoNET |date=26 March 2026 |language=pt }}</ref> ({{IPA|pt-BR|dɐˈnilu ˈsɐ̃tus}}) is a Brazilian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A]] club [[Botafogo FR|Botafogo]] and the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]].

Born in [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Danilo was in the youth academy of [[Esporte Clube Bahia|Bahia]], before stints at [[Esporte Clube Jacuipense|Jacuipense]] and [[Pituaçu Futebol Clube Cajazeiras|PFC Cajazeiras]], where he was spotted by [[SE Palmeiras|Palmeiras]] in 2018. After progressing steadily in Palmeiras' youth ranks, he made his first team Série A debut in 2020 at the age of 19. He was part of the Palmeiras teams who won the [[Copa Libertadores]] consecutively in 2020 and 2021, solidifying himself as a stalwart in the middle of the park and becoming a consistent first-team starter.

==Club career==
===Early career===
Born in [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], Bahia,<ref name=PAL/> Danilo represented [[Esporte Clube Bahia|Bahia]] as a youth before being released by the club. In 2017, at the age of 16, he joined [[Pituaçu Futebol Clube Cajazeiras|PFC Cajazeiras]] through a social project, after a short stint at [[Esporte Clube Jacuipense|Jacuipense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://falacajazeiras.com.br/danilo-ex-jogador-do-cajazeiras-e-c-comeca-a-brilhar-no-palmeiras/|title=Danilo: Ex jogador do Cajazeiras E.C. começa a brilhar no Palmeiras|trans-title=Danilo: former Cajazeiras E.C. player starts to shine at Palmeiras|publisher=Fala Cajazeiras|language=pt-BR|date=13 September 2020|accessdate=23 September 2020}}</ref> He made his senior debut for Cajazeiras on 5 May 2018, aged 17, by coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 4–0 [[Campeonato Baiano (lower levels)|Campeonato Baiano Segunda Divisão]] home routing of {{ill|Conquista Futebol Clube|lt=Conquista|pt}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbf.org.br/arquivos/tabela_sumulas/1210/ARQUIVO_SUMULA.PDF|title=PFC Cajazeiras 4x0 Conquista|publisher=[[Federação Bahiana de Futebol]]|language=pt-BR|accessdate=23 September 2020|archive-date=8 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208015859/http://fbf.org.br/arquivos/tabela_sumulas/1210/ARQUIVO_SUMULA.PDF|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Palmeiras===
In 2018, Danilo joined [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]], initially for the under-17s.<ref name=PAL>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmeiras.com.br/pt-br/noticias/volante-danilo-e-a-setima-criadaacademia-a-estrear-no-time-principal-em-2020/|title=Volante Danilo é a sétima #CriadaAcademia a estrear no time principal em 2020|trans-title=Defensive midfielder Danilo is the seventh ''#CriadaAcademia'' to debut in the main squad in 2020|publisher=SE Palmeiras|language=pt-BR|date=6 September 2020|accessdate=23 September 2020}}</ref> He progressed through the youth setup, being later a starter for the under-20s before making his first team – and [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A|Série A]] – debut on 6 September 2020, replacing fellow youth graduate [[Patrick de Paula]] in a 2–1 away win against [[Red Bull Bragantino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lance.com.br/palmeiras/cria-academia-danilo-estreia-luxa-avisa-jovem-com-potencial.html|title=Cria da Academia, Danilo estreia e Luxa avisa: 'Jovem com potencial'|trans-title=Youth graduate of the ''Academia'', Danilo debuts and ''Luxa'' warns: 'Youngster with potential'|publisher=[[Lance!]]|language=pt-BR|date=7 September 2020|accessdate=23 September 2020}}</ref>

On 10 September 2020, Danilo was bought outright by ''Verdão'', signing a permanent five-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/times/palmeiras/noticia/palmeiras-anuncia-compra-do-volante-danilo.ghtml|title=Palmeiras anuncia compra do volante Danilo|trans-title=Palmeiras announce the purchase of defensive midfielder Danilo|publisher=[[Grupo Globo|GloboEsporte.com]]|language=pt-BR|date=10 September 2020|accessdate=23 September 2020}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on 2 December, netting his team's fifth in a 5–0 [[Copa Libertadores]] home routing of [[Delfín S.C.|Delfín SC]].

===Nottingham Forest===
In January 2023, Danilo joined [[Premier League]] side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] for an estimated £16&nbsp;million fee, signing a six-and a-half-year deal with the English club in the process.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 January 2023 |title=Forest Complete Danilo Signing |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2023/january/16/forest-complete-danilo-signing/ |access-date=17 January 2023 |website=Nottingham Forest Football Club}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=16 January 2023 |title=Forest seal signing of Palmeiras midfielder Danilo |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64298998 |access-date=17 January 2023}}</ref>

On the opening day of the 2024–25 season against [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], he suffered a leg injury in the 8th minute, which could see him miss the entirety of the campaign.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 August 2024 |title=Danilo suffers potential season ending injury |url=https://twitter.com/footballontnt/status/1824812784946741469 |access-date=17 August 2024 |website=X}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2025}}

===Botafogo===
On 18 July 2025, Danilo moved to [[Campeonato Brasileiro Série A]] side [[Botafogo FR|Botafogo]] on a four-year deal for a reported fee of $25,000,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.botafogo.com.br/noticias/botafogo-acerta-contratacao-danilo-contrato-julho-2029|title=Botafogo oficializa a contratação do volante Danilo|date=9 August 2023|website=www.botafogo.com.br}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2025/july/18/danilo-departs/|title=Danilo departs|first=Nottingham Forest Football|last=Club|date=18 July 2025|website=Nottingham Forest Football Club}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6502174/2025/07/18/nottingham-forest-danilo-botafogo/|title=Nottingham Forest's Danilo completes Botafogo transfer|first1=Nick|last1=Miller|first2=Matt|last2=Woosnam|date=18 July 2025|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>

==International career==
In June 2022, Danilo was called up to the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]] by head coach [[Tite (football manager)|Tite]] for [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendlies]] against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]]. However, he did not feature in either of the matches and was left out of the final squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].

Danilo was recalled to the national side, now by coach [[Carlo Ancelotti]], in March 2026, for a set of friendly matches against [[France national football team|France]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] later that month.<ref>{{cite news |date=16 March 2026 |title=Brazil: Brentford's Igor Thiago and Bournemouth's Rayan receive first call-ups |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c8eg0y22w2ro |access-date=17 March 2026 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

